# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2018-bavarian-state-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] The 1919 Bavarian state election was held on 12 January and 2 February 1919 to elect the 180 members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] The 1920 Bavarian state election was held on 6 June 1920 to elect the 155 members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] Following the incorporation of Coburg into Bavaria, the Coburg Landtag elected two Social Democratic Party members and one German Democratic Party member to join the Bavarian Landtag from 1 July 1920.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] A by-election was held in Coburg on 7 November 1920 to elect the region's three members to the Bavarian Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] The 1924 Bavarian state election was held on 6 April and 4 May 1924 to elect the 129 members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] The 1928 Bavarian state election was held on 20 May 1928 to elect the 128 members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] The 1932 Bavarian state election was held on 24 April 1932 to elect the 128 members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1919-bavarian-state-election] In the aftermath of the election, Heinrich Held was reinstated as Minister President of Bavaria in what became the Held IV cabinet, forming a minority coalition with the DNVP.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The **1950 Bavarian state election** was held on 26 November 1950 to elect the members of the 2nd Landtag of Bavaria.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The outgoing government was a majority of the Christian Social Union (CSU) led by Minister-President Hans Ehard.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The CSU suffered an enormous decline of 25 percentage points, and lost first place in the overall vote to the opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) by a slight margin.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] However, the CSU narrowly retained a plurality of 64 seats to the SPD's 63 thanks to the regional apportionment of seats.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] Two new parties entered the Landtag: the Bavaria Party (BP) with 18% of the vote and the All-German Bloc (BHE) with 12%.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP) also improved to 7%.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The CSU subsequently formed a grand coalition with the SPD, and Minister-President Ehard continued in office.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The 1950 election remains the CSU's worst performance in a Bavarian election and the only occasion they did not win a plurality of the vote.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] After the 1946 state elections, the CSU had won a majority of seats in the Landtag, and proceeded to form a coalition government with the SPD and right-wing populist WAV under Minister-President Hans Ehard.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The coalition, however, was short lived.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] On 20 June 1947, WAV party chairman and Minister for Denazification Alfred Loritz was ousted by his fellow party-members over a power struggle involving a fellow state delegate, Karl Meissner.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] Four days later, on 24 June, Loritz was dismissed from his post on charges of blackmail and patronage.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] He subsequently was arrested on 19 July 1947, before escaping custody, being re-arrested, and eventually found asylum in Switzerland in April 1948.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] In his place, a CSU attorney, Ludwig Hagenauer was appointed.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] Only three months after the Loritz episode, all of the SPD ministers within the government resigned, ending the coalition government, which lasted for under a year.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The CSU then ruled alone (still as a majority government) for the remaining three years.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] In the intervening time, Ehard mainly battled with other member of his party to pass the Basic Law.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The electoral system was changed since the 1946 election, now every voter has two votes.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] One for local district candidate (first vote) and one for a constituency candidate (second vote).
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the First Landtag of Bavaria.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] With the WAV now essentially collapsed due to factional disputes, the right-wing vote was scattered over several different parties, the most important being the GB/BHE and the Bavaria Party, which capitalized on nationalism and took votes away from both the WAV and CSU.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] With the right-wing vote now spread thin, the SPD captured a majority of the first and second votes combined, but were still one seat off of being tied with the CSU's delegation, and neither party being close to a majority.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] After 17 days of negotiations, a mass coalition between the CSU, SPD, and GB/BHE was declared.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1950-bavarian-state-election] On 18 December 1950, Hans Ehard received 131 votes in the Landtag to serve a second term as Minister-President, with 5 votes against, and 36 members abstaining.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The **1954 Bavarian state election** was held on 28 November 1954 to elect the members of the Third Bavarian Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] It is notable for being both the only time that a member of the SPD was elected as Minister-President and the only time that the CSU was in the opposition.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In the previous 1950 election, the CSU had suffered a major blow by losing 40 of its seats within the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] After strenuous negotiations that lasted 17 days, a broad coalition was formed between the CSU, SPD and GB/BHE, with Hans Ehard retaining in his position as Minister-President.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] With a vote of 131–5, with 36 abstentions he was elected as Minister-President within the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The second Ehard term did not go without scandals, however.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In 1946, the Holocaust survivor Philipp Auerbach had been appointed as state commissioner of reparations.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] His tasks were many, but there was a particular focus on managing the repatriation of and administering reparations checks to those in displacement camps.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Auerbach was described as having "acquired the funds for reparations payments in marginally legal, brilliant, and unorthodox ways", but that was not enough.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The Bavarian government did not pay the full amount for reparation claims above $600.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Instead, claimants received a first installment in cash and a second in the form of compensations checks that could not be renewed until 1 January 1954.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Displaced persons, who were often desperate for money, would sell those notes to for 30 to 50 percent of their face values to banks.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The banks by 1950 had bought up about $2 million worth of these notes.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Minister-President Ehard gave approval for such transactions.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Auerbach eventually lodged a complaint to the state Justice Ministry in December 1950 that residency permits were being counterfeited for money, which blocked the way of actual claimants from receiving funds.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Justice Minister Josef Müller however, turned that on its head and blamed Auerbach for such behaviour.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] On 27 January 1951, the Bavarian police occupied the state reparations office in Munich in search of evidence of fraud and mishandling on the part of Auerbach.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] While his methods (which included state-backed loans secured by Nazi property) were unorthodox, they were legal, and there was no evidence of him personally enriching himself.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In the proceedings, it was also discovered that he had falsely claimed the title of doctor.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Auerbach took his own life in prison on 14 August 1952.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] While the Auerbach Affair hung over much of Ehard's tenure, none of the intrigue of the first term occurred, and the coalition stayed intact.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The only immediate result was the forced resignation of the Justice Minister in 1952.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The CSU managed to recoup some of their 1950 losses, gaining 19 seats in the 1954 elections, at the primary expense of the BP and GB/BHE which had divided the right-wing vote in 1950.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Under the leadership of the state SPD chair, Waldemar von Knoeringen, the SPD brokered a *Viererkoalition* (coalition-of-four) between themselves, the FDP, the BP, and GB/BHE which stemmed from a collective skepticism of the CSU.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] On 14 December 1954 Wilhelm Hoegner was voted in as Minister-President.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In light of this, disputes broke out within the CSU, which led to the resignation of Hans Ehard as party chair in January 1955, but he still retained his position as President of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The Hoegner government fell into a major scandal of its own, but it did not manage to come out intact like Ehard's had.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In 1951, businessman Karl Freisehner had approached the government about casino operating concessions in his name.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] While this was rejected, several Landtag members had received a bribe of 50,000 marks in order to vote yes.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] With enough pressure, the Bavarian government did give the licences in April 1955.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Soon afterwards, the CSU had launched a parliamentary investigation into the opening of the casinos.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] One of the recipients of the 50,000 mark check was a CSU deputy, Franz Michel, who came forwards to his other party members.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Later on he'd claim he burned the check.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The crusade against the bribery was now led by Friedrich Zimmermann, who reportedly had incriminating evidence on the Deputy Minister-President and co-founder of the BP, Joseph Baumgartner.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] In 1957, Baumgartner and Minister of the Interior August Geislhöringer (also a member of the BP) resigned in face of these allegations, and the coalition collapsed.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] This wasn't enough for Zimmerman and he eventually got what he wanted: in January 1959 Freisehner came forward with documents detailing payments made to the two ministers.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] Both were sentenced to jail, with Baumgartner receiving two years in prison, and Geislhöringer one and a half.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] It would later be revealed that the documents Freisehner had presented were most likely forged, however by that point it didn't matter, the BP had managed to destroy its own reputation.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The *Viererkoalition* officially collapsed on 8 October 1957. due to a combination of the Casino Affair, and the CDU/CSU victory in the 1957 federal election.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The right-wing parties abandoned the SPD in reaction to the election, and Hoegner submitted his resignation on 9 October 1957.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] CSU politician Hanns Seidel was chosen as Minister-President, and formed a coalition with the FDP and GB/BHE, which would last through the 1958 state elections.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/1954-bavarian-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the Second Landtag of Bavaria.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The **2018 Bavarian state election** took place on 14 October 2018 to elect the 180 members of the 18th Landtag of Bavaria.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The outgoing government was a majority of the Christian Social Union in Bavaria (CSU), led by Minister President Markus Söder.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The CSU recorded its worst result since 1950 with 37% of votes, a decline of over ten percentage points, although it remained by far the largest party in the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The SPD, which had previously been the second largest party, fell to fifth place with just 10%.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Greens gained 9 points and emerged as the second strongest party with 17.5%.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Free Voters of Bavaria (FW) gained 2.6 points and finished third with 11.6% of the total vote.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Alternative for Germany (AfD), which ran in Bavaria for the first time, placed fourth with 10%.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Free Democratic Party (FDP), which failed to enter the Landtag in 2013, narrowly re-entered with 5.1%, becoming the smallest party.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Turnout rose to 72%, up 9 points from under 64% in 2013.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The election was influenced by the condition of the federal CDU/CSU–SPD government following two crises in the preceding months: the so-called asylum quarrel in June and July followed by the controversy around Hans-Georg Maaßen in September.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] CSU leader Horst Seehofer played a major role in both events.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Four days before the Bavarian election, federal SPD leader Andrea Nahles criticised Chancellor Angela Merkel, accusing her of a "lack of leadership".
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] As a result of the election, the CSU lacked a majority and formed a coalition government with the Free Voters.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] According to the Bavarian Constitution, the election must be held on a Sunday "at the earliest 59 months, at the latest 62 months" after the preceding state elections which took place on 15 September 2013.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] This would theoretically allow an election date between 19 August and 11 November 2018, but in practice the elections since 1978 have always taken place between mid-September and mid-October.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Bavarian state government proposed 14 October 2018 as the election date on 9 January 2018 and officially set it on 20 February after hearing the parties to the state parliament.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The deadline for determining the population figures, which are decisive for the distribution of the 180 Landtag mandates among the seven Bavarian administrative districts and a possible new division of the constituencies, was 15 June 2016 (33 months after the election of the previous Landtag).
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] On this basis, the Bavarian Ministry of the Interior had to submit a constituency report to the Landtag until 36 months after the election This was done on 6 September 2016.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Delegates to the internal constituency meetings could be appointed at the earliest 43 months after the preceding election, i.e. since 16 April 2017.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The actual district candidates had been eligible since 16 July 2017.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The actual election proposals and any necessary signatures had to be submitted by 2 August 2018.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Bavaria, in line with the rest of the country, uses mixed-member proportional representation to elect its members of the Landtag.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Party representation is not apportioned statewide, the distribution of seats takes place separately within the seven administrative districts (*Regierungsbezirke*), which are referred to in the electoral law as constituencies.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The constituencies are divided into districts in which one member is directly elected.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The number of single member districts is about half the number of seats in the constituency.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] If a party wins more district seats in a constituency than it would be entitled to based on a strictly proportional system (these extra seats are termed overhang seats), these seats are added to the constituency.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] To compensate the other parties for the overhang, leveling seats are added at the constituency level too.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] There is no statewide adjustment of the seats.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Only parties and groups of voters who obtain at least 5% of the total votes (sum of first and second votes) in Bavaria participate in the distribution of seats.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] This threshold also applies to winning single-member districts; a party will forfeit all its district seats that it won if the party did not meet the 5% statewide threshold, with the forfeited district seats going to the second-place candidate.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Unlike the other German states (and also countries using MMP), Bavaria uses an open-list system for its party-list seats.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Voters not only cast a vote for a candidate in their district, but they also cast a vote for a list candidate in their region.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] For the distribution of list seats, all district candidates are also constituency candidates with their parties.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The party may also nominate regional-only candidates.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] To prevent double voting, the constituency ballots in each district omit the candidates running in that district.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] A candidate (if he or she did not win his or her district) is ranked within his or her list by the number of first votes he or she receives within the district plus the number of second votes he or she receives from voters elsewhere in the region.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In this manner, voters collectively can produce a list that is different from what the party submitted, which can result in the defeat of candidates that would have been elected (and vice versa) had the election taken place under a closed-list system.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In the statutory constituency report of September 2016, the state government stated that the numerical distribution of the 180 state parliament seats among the constituencies would have to be changed due to changes in the number of inhabitants.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] It was recommended that a seat previously to be awarded in the Lower Franconia constituency be allocated to the Upper Bavaria constituency.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Within Upper Bavaria, the additional seat was used to reshape the single member districts in the state capital of Munich, as two of them — Giesing and Milbertshofen — exceeded the average population by more than 15 percent.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Upper Bavaria now has 31 single member districts for the 2018 elections, nine of which are accounted for by the state capital.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In March 2017, the CSU used the mandatory redistricting to redraw Munich's electoral districts.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In this, they were accused of gerrymandering; redistricting created a new *Stimmkreis München-Mitte* that was *packing* all parts of Munich that at the time favored the SPD.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Greens eventually won the district by a huge margin.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The CSU was only partly successful in their gerrymandering, as they still lost four districts in Munich that were drawn to their advantage.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Since the state elections in Bavaria in 2013, the CSU again had the absolute majority of seats, as it did from 1962 to 2008.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The CSU also held the position of the senior partner in all but one governing coalition in Bavaria since the end of World War II, including every coalition since 1958.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In December 2017, however, Minister President of Bavaria Horst Seehofer (CSU) finally declared his renunciation of the top candidate in the state elections in Bavaria in 2018, partly due to the poor performance of the CSU in the 2017 Bundestag elections.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In March 2018, he also resigned from his office as Minister President of Bavaria before the end of the parliamentary term.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The former Bavarian Finance Minister Markus Söder was elected as the new top CSU candidate and later also as Minister President of Bavaria in the state parliament.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In 2018, the CSU Markus Söder's government enacted the *Kreuzpflicht*, an obligation to display crosses at the entrance of public buildings.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Söder has stated that the crosses are not to be seen as Christian symbols, but as symbols of Bavarian cultural identity.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Some observers have described the *Kreuzpflicht* as a measure to appeal to voters deserting the Christian democratic conservative CSU for the right-wing nationalist AfD party.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Also the CSU interior minister Horst Seehofer has taken a harder line on immigration.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The table below lists parties represented in the 17th Landtag of Bavaria since 2013.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The AfD, having been founded earlier that year, did not run yet.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] A leaders' debate between Minister President Markus Söder (CSU) and Ludwig Hartmann (Alliance 90/The Greens) took place on 26 September 2018.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The Bayerischer Rundfunk justified the party selection with the result of the *Bayerntrend* of September 12, 2018, according to which CSU and Greens can hope for the most votes in the election.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] SPD Secretary-General Uli Grötsch described this decision as "completely absurd".
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] A programme with representatives of the other five parties, whose survey results were above or close to the five percent hurdle, followed on 28 September 2018: Natascha Kohnen (SPD), Hubert Aiwanger (Free Voters), Martin Sichert (AfD), Martin Hagen (FDP) and Ates Gürpinar (The Left).
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The first programme was moderated by BR editor-in-chief Christian Nitsche, the second by Ursula Heller.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] On behalf of the RTL/n-tv *Trendbarometer*, Forsa Institute interviewed the survey participants about the "biggest problems at state level".
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In Bavaria, 34 percent of those surveyed named the CSU and Prime Minister Markus Söder, 28 percent named refugees, and 26 percent named "the situation on the housing market".
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Infratest dimap asked respondents to the ARD primary election survey which topic is very important for their election decision.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The voter turnout in the city of Munich remained high.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Until 2 p.m. it was 54.6 percent including the postal voters.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] In 2013, the turnout at that time was 49.7 percent.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The final total turnout was recorded as 72.3% of eligible voters.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The percentages indicate the proportion of respondents who would most like the particular coalition available for selection.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The percentages do not sum to 100% due to respondents who did not indicate a preference.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] Before the election, CSU faction leader Thomas Kreuzer declared that the CSU would not form a coalition with the AfD or the Greens after the election.
[src:2018-bavarian-state-election/2018-bavarian-state-election] The CSU agreed on a coalition deal to govern with the Free Voters of Bavaria on 4 November 2018.
